    "summary": "Emperor Justinian I (r. 527–565 AD) was the most ambitious and consequential ruler of the Byzantine Empire — a Macedonian-born emperor who dreamed of restoring the full Roman Empire, came closer to achieving it than anyone since Theodosius I, and left behind a legal, architectural, and theological legacy that shaped Europe for a millennium. Justinian's reign saw the reconquest of North Africa from the Vandals (533 AD), Italy from the Ostrogoths (535–554 AD, [[event:2903|Justinian's Reconquest]]), and southern Spain from the Visigoths — briefly reuniting much of the old western empire under Constantinople's control. The price was devastating: the reconquest of Italy destroyed it, triggering decades of war and population collapse.\n\nJustinian's greatest lasting achievement was the [[event:2121|Corpus Juris Civilis]] (529–534 AD) — a comprehensive codification of Roman law that became the foundation of legal systems across continental Europe. The [[event:2120|Hagia Sophia]] (completed 537 AD) remains one of the greatest architectural achievements in history. His reign was also marked by the devastating [[event:2122|Plague of Justinian]] (541 AD onward), the first documented pandemic of bubonic plague, which killed perhaps a third of the Mediterranean world's population and fatally undermined his reconquest projects. The theological controversies of his reign — particularly his attempts to resolve the Monophysite dispute — produced endless strife. His complex relationship with his wife Empress Theodora (who came from a circus background and proved a formidable political partner) shaped Byzantine court politics throughout the reign.",
